commentBody:
@Lewis 

I liked GNU and AISLE. Smiled when I solved them.

🍑🍍🍒🍓

@Chris 

I did the same thing. Even when I realized that the circles held FIGHTING WORDS, I failed to notice that BAt, while theme-related, didn’t work as part of a theme answer. 

I managed to come in one second faster than my average, but still, that T and that N ate up some time.

@Puzzlemucker 

Wow, that Is a story for the ages!

Way to demonstrate grace under pressure! You obviously made an impression!

@sotto voce 

I was pleasantly reminded of MINOLTA, too. It was the first SLR I ever had, bought while I was still in high school. 

It’s still in my closet, along with several lenses acquired over the years. But I haven’t shot film in decades.

@Kris T 

I could live more easily with a “Batman theme” earworm than one of “That’s Amore.”

I actually filled in PIZZA PIE without reading the clue because nothing else could have gone there. It wasn’t until I read the review of the puzzle on Diary of a Crossword Fiend that I saw what the clue was.

@Kris T

Not my favorite puzzle but I'll defend the constructors with respect to 37A. Had it been clued as "What Yosemite Sam might say to Bugs before demanding a duel", you might have a point. However, "fighting words" is well worn in less idiomatic contexts, to say nothing of the legal doctrine which speakers tend to cite within the bounds of proper grammar: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fighting_words" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fighting_words</a>

Furthermore, the clue made no mention of fictional dialogue, let alone Westerns.

@Grant 

I’m pretty sure I have seen both “niblick” and “mashie” in crossword puzzles. Not necessarily NYT and not on an “easy” day.

I’m with Barry Ancona on ONE IRON. I’ve never been interested in golf, but it seems like fairly common knowledge that golf clubs are either “irons” or “woods,” and the different ones are numbered. It’s from crossword puzzles that I learned the significance of the numbers.

@Cherry 

When you’re surfing the web, and you come to a grinding halt at a website that catches your eye, that is an ESTOP.

(Emus please publish the logic for the program that auto-filters comments so that maybe we know when it is unnecessary to pad comments like this)

@Mean Old Lady

Because he didn’t post it immediately after another brief comment. 

The filter is set to weed out spam. Short comments, posted in short succession, will get filtered out, because that is exactly what a spammer would do. Space out your comments and you won’t have a problem. Add another sentence and you won’t have a problem.

@Jon 
I have seen EIDER many times, MINOLTA not so much. 

Eider down is the cashmere of feathers, a duvet made with it will cost much more than a goose down duvet.

@G 

“Bldg.” is an abbreviation. DORM is a shortened word formed from dormitory, but it is a word unto itself. 

To RECAP: Real abbreviations get markers. Shortened words don’t. Period. Or, no period.

@Eric Hougland 

I always assumed to goofy fight scenes were part of the camp.

It’s also funny to compare Adam West’s Batman dad bod in his spandex suit (with the fashionable utility belt!) to today’s Batmen with their sculpted armor wear.

@MmmmHmmm 

Rite Aid might be in bankruptcy and hemorrhaging money, but it is far from out of business.  According to Wikipedia, it has 2000 stores, and has been closing down 500 as part of the bankruptcy.  Although it is not clear whether this is part of or in addition to the 2000 stores, that's still a lot of stores.

Rite Aid has left entire regional markets, but it is still a strong presence in many others, including here in New York.

@Lewis

“Not down, in a way,” for SIP was my favorite, mainly because I had filled it in from the crosses, so when I first looked at the answer I was puzzled. Pun intended! 

I always look forward to your lists.

@Bonnie 

No, I was still in grade school in Burlington, Vermont, when the Batman movie came out. I remember my parents taking my brother and me to a drive-in to see it. 

I don’t remember how I learned that the premiere was at the Paramount here. Probably a Facebook post by the Paramount on some anniversary of the premiere.
